  "preamble": "Final-obstruent devoicing is a phonetic process where voiced consonants, such as the bilabial stop [b], lose their voicing at the end of a word or syllable. This shift is a characteristic feature of several language families, including Germanic and Slavic, where it serves to simplify the articulation before a pause.",
